President Biden addressed the tragedy that occurred during a holiday parade in Wisconsin, expressing condolences to the families affected and praising the first responders. He then highlighted the progress made in the US economy since the COVID-19 pandemic, including record job growth, a drop in the unemployment rate, and a surge in small business creation. The President acknowledged the challenges still faced, such as rising costs for American families, but emphasized the strength of the economy and the ability to address inflation. He announced his nomination of Jerome Powell for a second term as Chair of the Federal Reserve and Lael Brainard as Vice Chair, citing their leadership, expertise, and bipartisan support. Both nominees expressed their commitment to supporting the economy, addressing inflation, and serving the American people. The President concluded by thanking the nominees' families and wishing everyone a happy Thanksgiving.